<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-956-668  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 956 668.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Dec 11 1989 v11 n50 p65(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Resolution evolution: inexpensive 16-bit VGA boards that helpusers sharpen their images. (Hardware Review) (includes relatedarticle on testing methods) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Douglas, Sally J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Video Graphics Array was introduced by IBM in 1987.andP;  Sincethen a large number of vendors have brought out VGA boards, whichhave become popular among business users who have all butabandoned EGA and other standards.andP;  Seven very new and inexpensive16-bit VGA graphics boards are evaluated for performance, ease ofuse, setup and documentation.andP;  Ahead Systems' VGA Wizard is thebest overall, and Ahead's other offering, the VGA Wizard/Deluxe,also scored high marks.andP;  Everex Systems' Viewpoint and GenoaSystems' Super VGA 6400 also did very well.andP;  The performances ofHeadland Technology's Video Seven VGA 1024i and Boca Research'sSuper VGA were about equal, and the Renaissance GRX RVGA II camein last.andP;  Different boards are equipped with different amounts ofRAM, different software drivers and varying resolutions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ahead Systems Inc. (products)Boca Research Inc. (products)Everex Systems Inc. (products)Genoa Systems Corp. (products)Video Seven Inc. (products)Renaissance GRX Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    EVRX; RENX.andO;Product:   Ahead Systems VGA Wizard (Graphics board)Ahead Systems VGA Wizard/Deluxe (Graphics board)Boca Research Super VGA (Graphics board)Everex Systems Viewpoint (Graphics board)Genoa Super VGA 6400 (Graphics board)Headland Technology Video Seven VGA 1024i (Graphics board).andO;Topic:     EvaluationGraphics Boards-CardsHigh Resolution.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Report card: 16-bit VGA card. (table)Benchmarks: 16-bit VGA board speed tests. (table)Product summaries for each of 6 VGA boards. (table)andM;</DESCR